**Take-home message**: Not fully read, but the main takeaway is there: we need to engage in critical readings of what 'failure' means as a way of *describing* the mechanisms and factors that are in play when categorizing something as 'failure' or success. The 'failing forward' approach, where failure is seen as a precondition for success is narrowed for several reasons, but mostly because it reduces the factors that cause failure to those that **can** be changed by the researchers themselves, obscuring those that underlie or are structural.

> n contrast to the exploitation of othersâ€™ failures to further a particular approach, this growing narrative directly acknowledges peopleâ€™s own role in past failures. Proponents of this focus on failure in conservation argue that people tend to report and share successes, but that a lot more can be learned from failure, and that people need to feel safe both to fail and to admit to this failure in order to foster learning (Catalano et al., 2019; Redford & Taber, 2000).

 This is certainly JOTE's aim: to create a 'safe-space', a venue for making everyone's personal failure as a stepping-stone for community-level success.

> A major assumption in these emerging conservation initiatives that seek to learn from failure is that the root causes of failure can be standardized across cases and common lessons drawn to improve future interventions, such as has been done in other sectors like aviation, medicine, business and technology. However, due to the strong emphasis on analyzing failure and success in direct relation to conservationistsâ€™ goals and intentions, it is no surprise that acknowledgement of failures and proposed solutions have similarly been strongly linked to implementation issues.

> While some studies point to barriers related to broader economic and political factors, such as an â€˜â€˜overriding imperative for productionâ€, such barriers are often reframed as merely providing â€˜â€˜no incentive for conservationâ€ (Catalano et al., 2019: 4), thus neglecting to consider the underlying reasons for documented dynamics like economic profitability or weak political will. > The emerging model for embracing (and in some cases even celebrating) failure in conservation has therefore focused particularly on issues of design and implementation, rather than on fundamentally questioning the nature of adopted approaches. Approaches have become grounded in local level pilot/testing sites for innovation, as well as exploration aggregated into a standardized global evidence base where â€˜fail-safeâ€™ cultures are encouraged to learn and adapt or â€˜scaleâ€™ approaches. Yet such projects typically operate at a superficial level, never fully engaging with nor reflecting the complex, messy, political realities that characterize biodiversity governance (Balboa, 2018; Li, 2016; Massarella et al., 2020; Myers et al., 2018), leading to a number of potential implications that will be explored in the next section.

 The interrogation of what caused something to fail is reduced to identifying the factors that **can** be changed, thus confining the improvement within the expertise / methodology / approach of the researchers. A critical approach would require to abandon the idea of finding something to fix, rather it would be about finding the factors (tweakable or not) that have caused the failure.

> The criteria for judging failure can even strategically shift over time, as evidenced by how many conservation policies are increasingly criticized for failing to demonstrate efficiency and profitability, even though this was peripheral to original aims (Beunen et al., 2013; Boda, 2016).

 This is why JOTE's focus on history as a critical approach to failure is useful: showing the changes in what we consider success/failure and their contingency on context.
